Lab 4

We will again work with the meteorological data presented in lecture.

The objective of the lab is to examine the association between weekly average dew point and wind speed in four regions of the US and by elevation.

met <- met %>% filter(temp >= -17)

met <- met %>%
  filter(temp != 9999, wind.sp != 9999, vis.dist != 99999, dew.point != 9999, rh != 999)

met <- met %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))



met <- met %>%
  mutate(region = case_when(
    lat >= 39.71 & lon < -98.00 ~ "NW",  # Northwest
    lat >= 39.71 & lon >= -98.00 ~ "NE", # Northeast
    lat < 39.71 & lon < -98.00 ~ "SW",   # Southwest
    lat < 39.71 & lon >= -98.00 ~ "SE"   # Southeast
  ))

met <- met %>%
  mutate(elevation_cat = case_when(
    elev < 200 ~ "Low",
    elev >= 200 & elev < 1000 ~ "Medium",
    elev >= 1000 ~ "High"
  ))

##3. Use geom_violin to examine the wind speed and dew point by region You saw how to use geom_boxplot in class. Try using geom_violin instead (take a look at the help). (hint: You will need to set the x aesthetic to 1)

met%>%
  filter(!(region %in% NA)) %>%
ggplot()+geom_violin(mapping = aes(y=wind.sp, x=1)) +facet_wrap(~region, nrow=3)
met%>%
  filter(!(region %in% NA)) %>%
ggplot()+geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y=dew.point, fill=region)) +facet_wrap(~region, nrow=1)

4. Use geom_jitter with stat_smooth to examine the association between dew point and wind speed by region

ggplot(met, aes(x = dew.point, y = wind.sp, color = region)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1, height = 0, alpha = 0.5) +  # Jittered points with color by region
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, formula = y ~ x, aes(group = region)) +  # Linear regression lines by region
  labs(x = "Dew Point", y = "Wind Speed") +  # Axis labels
  theme_minimal()  # Minimal theme

## Use geom_bar to create barplots of the weather stations by elevation category colored by region

ggplot(met, aes(x = factor(elev), fill = region)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +  # Create bars with dodge positioning
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +  # Change colors using Brewer palette
  labs(x = "Elevation Category", y = "Number of Stations", fill = "Region") +  # Axis labels and legend title
  ggtitle("Weather Stations by Elevation Category and Region") +  # Title
  theme_minimal() +  # Minimal theme
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability

Use stat_summary to examine mean dew point and wind speed by region with standard deviation error bars

met <- na.omit(met)

# plot for dew point
ggplot(met, aes(x = region, y = dew.point)) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl", geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl", geom = "point", size = 3) +
  labs(x = "Region", y = "Dew Point") +
  ggtitle("Mean Dew Point by Region with Standard Deviation Error Bars") +
  theme_minimal()
#  plot for wind speed
ggplot(met, aes(x = region, y = wind.sp)) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl", geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_sdl", geom = "point", size = 3) +
  labs(x = "Region", y = "Wind Speed") +

  theme_minimal()

7. Make a map showing the spatial trend in relative humidity in the US

library(leaflet)

met <- na.omit(met)

#color palette with custom colors
colors <- colorFactor(
  palette = c("blue", "green", "yellow", "red"),
  domain = met$region
)

# leaflet map
m <- leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  setView(lng = -98.00, lat = 39.71, zoom = 4)  

#  markers for the top 10 places in relative humidity
top10 <- met[order(-met$rh), ][1:10, ]
m <- m %>%
  addMarkers(
    data = top10,
    lat = ~lat,
    lng = ~lon,
    label = ~paste0("Place: ", rownames(top10), "<br>Relative Humidity: ", round(rh, 2), "%"),
    clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions()
  )

# legend values
legend_values <- levels(colors)

# Add a legend
m <- m %>%
  addLegend(
    "bottomright",
    pal = colors,
    values = legend_values,
    title = "Region",
    opacity = 1
  )

# Display the map
m
